ish: habitational name from any of the many places in England named with Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, glade’, including Lee in Buckinghamshire, Essex, Hampshire, Kent, and Shropshire, and Lea in Cheshire, Derbyshire, Herefordshire, Lancashire, Lincolnshire, and Wiltshire."],"variants":[{"name":"Ley","meanings":["English: variant of   Lee  .","German: from a medieval personal name, <i>Eloy</i>, from Latin <i>Eligius</i> (see   Eligio  ), a Christian saint's name.","German (Rhineland): topographic name from Middle High German <i>leie</i> ‘rock, stone, slate’, or a habitational name from any of several places called with this word. Compare   Leier  ."]},{"name":"Lees","meanings":["English and Scottish: topographic name from Middle English <i>lees</i> ‘fields, arable land’, plural of <i>lee</i> (see   Lee  ), or from Middle English <i>lese</i> ‘pasture, meadow’ (Old English <i>lǣs</i>).","English: habitational name fromLeece or Lees in Lancashire, or Leese in Cheshire, all named from OldEnglish <i>lēas</i> ‘woodland clearings’ (plural of<i>lēah</i>), or from Leece in Cumbria, which was probably namedwith a Celtic word, <i>lïss</i> ‘hall, court, the principalhouse in a district’.","English: variant of   Leece   1."]},{"name":"Lay","meanings":["English: variant of   Lee  .","Scottish: shortened form of   McClay  .","German: habitational name from any of the places so named, in the Rhineland near Koblenz and in Bavaria, from <i>lay(h)</i>, a word meaning ‘stone, rock, slate’."]},{"name":"Laye","meanings":["English: variant of   Lee  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 李, based on its Cantonese pronunciation. See   Li   1."]},{"name":"Lie","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Oystein, Sven, Thor.  German Hans, Gunther, Hilde.  Korean Han, Chang Ho, Chen, Chun, Hok, Jung, Kam, Liang, Lie, Ling, Shuen, Yung.","Norwegian: variant of   Li   11, a habitational name from any of numerous farmsteads named Li, from Old Norse <i>hlíth</i> ‘mountain slope, hillside’. In Norway this is the most frequent spelling.","German: unexplained."]},{"name":"Layman","meanings":["English: topographic name for a dweller by a woodland clearing or a meadow, from Middle English <i>ley</i> + <i>man</i>. Compare   Lee  .","English: nickname from <i>layman</i>, a word denoting an uneducated person.","Americanized form of German   Lehmann  ."]},{"name":"Lea","meanings":["English: variant of   Lee  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surnames 李 and 利, see   Li   1 and 3."]},{"name":"Lye","meanings":["English: variant of   Lee   1, a topographic name for someone who lived near a patch of arable land, or a habitational name from Lye in Herefordshire (with the same etymology).","Norwegian: habitational name from a farmstead in Rogaland named Lye, Old Norse <i>Lýgi</i> meaning ‘alliance, covenant’, used to denote a place sanctified by such an agreement, such as a court or council meeting place.","Altered form of German   Ley  ."]},{"name":"Saelee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Southeast Asian Chan, Kao, Nai, Chai, Cheng, Chien, Foo, Hin, Muang, Pao, Seng, Song, Sou.","Southeast Asian (Iu Mien): from the name of the Lee clan of the Iu Mien people from Laos + the Thai prefix <i>sae</i>, denoting a clan. Compare   Lee   8."]},{"name":"Leigh","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places (in at least sixteen counties, but especially Leigh in Lancashire) named either with the nominative case of Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’ (see   Lee  ) or with <i>lēage</i>, a late dative form of this word (see   Lye  ).","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 李, based on its Cantonese pronunciation. See   Li   1."]}]},{"name":"Margerie","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Margary  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margary","meanings":["The usual medieval vernacular form of   Margaret   (now also commonly spelled   Marjorie  ). This form of the name is preserved in the nursery rhyme ‘See-saw, Margery Daw’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margerie Lee was born in 1405, in Chorley, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of John Lee. She married Richard Brooke about 1429, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter."},"et":{"1405–":"1405–Surnud","1405–Female":"1405–Surnud","1400–1440":"1400–1440","1430–1475":"1430–1475","1442–1463":"1442–1463","–Male":"Surnud","about 1429":"umbes 1429","1400":"1400","1442":"1442","1475":"1475","1430":"1430","1463":"1463","1440":"1440","1405":"1405","Medeley, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Chorley,,Shropshire,England":"Chorley, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Leighton by Neston, Cheshire, England":"Leighton by Neston, Cheshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1405–":"1405–Kuollut","1405–Female":"1405–Kuollut","1400–1440":"1400–1440","1430–1475":"1430–1475","1442–1463":"1442–1463","–Male":"Kuollut","about 1429":"noin 1429","1400":"1400","1442":"1442","1475":"1475","1430":"1430","1463":"1463","1440":"1440","1405":"1405","Medeley, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Chorley,,Shropshire,England":"Chorley, Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Leighton by Neston, Cheshire, England":"Leighton by Neston, Cheshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1405–":"1405–Décédée","1405–Female":"1405–Décédée","1400–1440":"1400–1440","1430–1475":"1430–1475","1442–1463":"1442–1463","–Male":"Décédé","about 1429":"environ 1429","1400":"1400","1442":"1442","1475":"1475","1430":"1430","1463":"1463","1440":"1440","1405":"1405","Medeley, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Angleterre","Chorley,,Shropshire,England":"Chorley, Shropshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Leighton by Neston, Cheshire, England":"Leighton by Neston, Cheshire, Angleterre","England, United Kingdom":"Angleterre, Roy